        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date range is conjectured from the nature of Bridges’s enquiry and the publication dates of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> and <hi rend="italic">Descent.</hi> CD discussed the habit of dogs of rolling in carrion in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 281; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> was published in early 1871. Bridges may have surmised that CD would have considered the question after reading the chapter on dogs and cats in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 15–48; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> was published in early 1868. The identity of the author is conjectured from the allusion to residence in China; William Thomas Bridges was a lawyer in Hong Kong from 1851 to 1861 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2347.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Endacott 1962</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
